QDs have emerged as versatile tools for enhancing the efficacy of RT through their integration into hybrid, multimodal, and imaging systems [34,51]. Their unique optical and photophysical properties, coupled with their ability to generate ROS, make them ideal candidates for synergistic applications in cancer treatment [74]. In hybrid systems, quantum dots are combined with various therapeutic agents —such as bacteria, chemotherapeutics, and nanoparticles—to enhance the overall therapeutic response [34,40,74]. In multimodal systems, QDs are integrated alongside small molecules or radiation to amplify radiosensitization, induce apoptosis, and modulate oxidative stress, thereby optimizing tumor treatment while minimizing collateral damage to healthy tissues [40]. Additionally, QDs have gained prominence as imaging agents due to their high photostability and biocompatibility, enabling precise tumor localization and improved diagnostic accuracy through techniques such as MRI and PET [35,74]. This section delves into the transformative potential of quantum dots across these domains, highlighting their promising role in revolutionizing cancer radiotherapy (Fig. 1
